724942f-a.title: Manhattan: Lexington Avenue - 34th Street
724942f-a.text:
Lexington Avenue, east side, north from 34th Street,
showing the Packard School at the S.E. corner of East 35th
Street and the Protestant Episcopal Church of the Epiphany
at the N.E. corner of same.
The Protestant Episcopal Church of the Epiphany will
occupy a new church (to be erected) on York Avenue, at the
N.W. corner of East 74th Street, after nearly a century at
the N.E. corner of lexington Avenue and East 35th Street.
Since the sale of this property (May 1936) to Dr. Charles
V. Paterno, a real estate specialist, the congregation has
been using the St. Thomas Chapel on East 60th Street as a
temporary place of worship. The Reverend Dr. John Wallace
Suter Jr. has been the rector since the retirement of the
Reverend William T. Crocker in 1933, who had held the posi-
tion for 30 years.
This data was reported in TBE NEw YORE SUN of SATURDAY,
PEBRDARY 20, 1937.
Dr. Paterno tradec this cleared site in 1939 for an
apartment builcing on Central Park South. The new owner
is completing a modern apartment house here in June, 1940.
September 30, 1933
P. L. Sperr

712137f-a.title: Manhattan: 34th Street (East) - Lexington Avenue
712137f-a.text:

3rd Aves., and across the latter, showing at that point, the
34th Street station of the 3rd Ave. Elevated Line. To the right,
slightly west of 3rd Ave., is a motion picture theatre known as
the 34th St. Theatre.
This illustration is from "Occidente" of July 1934 and faces
page No. 65.
July 1934.
